==English==
{{commons}}
{{wikipedia}}
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/flæg/}}
*{{audio|en-us-flag.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:Rhymes: [[rhymes:English:-æɡ|-æɡ]]

===Etymology 1===
Of uncertain origin; compare Dutch [[flag#Dutch|flag]], Danish [[flæg]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# any of various plants with sword-shaped leaves, especially [[iris]]es; specifically, ''Iris pseudacorus''

====Derived terms====
*[[sweet flag]]

===Etymology 2===
Probably of Scandinavian origin; compare Icelandic [[flag#Icelandic|flag]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# ''(obsolete except in dialects)'' a slice of [[turf]], a [[sod]]
# a slab of stone, a [[flagstone]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb|flag|g|ed}}

# To lay down flagstones.
#: ''Fred is planning to flag his patio this weekend.''

===Etymology 3===
[[Image:Flyingrainbowflag.JPG|right|thumb|a flag]]
Origin unknown.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A piece of [[cloth]], often decorated with an emblem, used as a visual [[signal]] or [[symbol]].
# (''Nautical'') A flag flown by a ship to shown the presence on board of the [[admiral]]; the admiral himself, or his flagship
# The use of a flag, especially to indicate the start of a race or other event
# (''Computer Science'') A [[variable]] or memory location that stores a true-or-false, yes-or-no value, typically either recording the fact that a certain event has occurred or requesting that a certain optional action take place.
# (''Computer Science'') In a [[CLI|command line interface]], a notation requesting optional behavior or otherwise modifying the action of the command being invoked.

=====Synonyms=====
* (''Computer Science'', true-or-false value) [[Boolean]]
* (''Computer Science'', CLI notation) [[switch]]

